<section class="bg-plum-darkest text-cream py-20 md:py-24">
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-12">
    <div
      class="relative rounded-3xl border border-pink/30 bg-mauve/15 p-8 md:p-14 overflow-hidden"
    >
      <span
        class="inline-block px-3 py-1 rounded-full bg-pink/20 text-pink text-[10px] font-sans tracking-[0.2em] uppercase mb-6"
      >
        Our focus
      </span>
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl md:text-4xl mb-8 max-w-4xl">
        What kind of quantum biology are we interested in?
      </h2>
      <div
        class="max-w-3xl space-y-5 font-sans text-base text-cream/80 leading-relaxed"
      >
        <p>
          There are many "flavors" of quantum biology — from birds navigating
          magnetic fields, to quantum coherence in photosynthesis, to theories of
          consciousness in microtubules.
        </p>
        <p>
          At the Quantum Biology DAO, we're especially focused on experimentally
          testable quantum effects, with real-world relevance and clear
          theoretical grounding.
        </p>
        <p>
          So far, we've been particularly interested in two areas: <span
            class="text-pink-light font-semibold">low-field magnetic effects</span
          > and <span class="text-pink-light font-semibold"
            >the radical pair mechanism</span
          >.
        </p>
        <p>
          These mechanisms are promising because they make specific predictions
          and could explain a wide range of biological phenomena, from tadpole
          development to human fertility.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
